---
import '../styles/portfolio-home.css';
import { getCollection } from 'astro:content';

const baseRaw = import.meta.env.BASE_URL;
const base = baseRaw.endsWith('/') ? baseRaw : `${baseRaw}/`;

const posts = (await getCollection('blog'))
  .filter((p) => !p.data.draft)
  .sort((a, b) => new Date(b.data.date).valueOf() - new Date(a.data.date).valueOf());

/** Placeholder rows from your static HTML (published posts are listed above from the collection). */
const writingTeasers = [
  {
    title: 'Elasticsearch at 200M records: the index redesign nobody warns you about',
    cat: 'Search',
  },
  {
    title: 'Debugging hallucinations in a production multi-agent system at 2am',
    cat: 'LLMs',
  },
  {
    title: 'Why most agentic systems are over-engineered in the wrong places',
    cat: 'Opinion',
  },
  {
    title: 'LinkedIn AI agent — week 1 build log',
    cat: 'Build log',
  },
] as const;

const year = new Date().getFullYear();
const repoUrl = 'https://github.com/abhii26-dev/abhishek-shukla';

/** Put your PDF at `public/resume.pdf` (works with `base` on GitHub Pages). Or set to any absolute URL. */
const resumeUrl = `${base}resume.pdf`;

/** Full Calendly URL (link + iframe). Override with `PUBLIC_CALENDLY_URL` in `.env` if needed. */
const envCalendly = import.meta.env.PUBLIC_CALENDLY_URL;
const calendlyUrl =
  typeof envCalendly === 'string' && envCalendly.trim().length > 0
    ? envCalendly.trim()
    : 'https://calendly.com/aashu-dev26';
---

<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
  <head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8" />
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0" />
    <link rel="icon" type="image/svg+xml" href={`${base}favicon.svg`} />
    <meta name="generator" content={Astro.generator} />
    <title>Abhishek Shukla — AI Systems Engineer</title>
    <link rel="preconnect" href="https://fonts.googleapis.com" />
    <link rel="preconnect" href="https://fonts.gstatic.com" crossorigin />
    <link
      href="https://fonts.googleapis.com/css2?family=Instrument+Serif:ital@0;1&family=DM+Sans:wght@300;400;500&family=DM+Mono:wght@400;500&display=swap"
      rel="stylesheet"
    />
  </head>
  <body>
    <nav>
      <a href={`${base}`} class="nav-logo">Abhishek <span>Shukla</span></a>
      <ul class="nav-links">
        <li><a href="#work">Work</a></li>
        <li><a href="#projects">Projects</a></li>
        <li><a href="#writing">Writing</a></li>
        <li><a href="#contact">Contact</a></li>
      </ul>
      <div class="nav-dot">Open to work</div>
    </nav>

    <div class="hero">
      <div class="hero-eyebrow">Software Engineer · AI Systems · India</div>
      <h1>
        I solve problems.<br />
        I ship AI that works.<br />
        I do the <em>right thing.</em>
      </h1>
      <div class="hero-bio reveal">
        <p>
          My name is Abhishek Shukla. I'm a software engineer who has spent the last 3+ years building AI
          systems that work in production — not in notebooks, not in demos, but in environments handling <strong
            >millions of requests across hundreds of millions of records.</strong
          >
          The satisfaction isn't in the cleverness of the architecture. It's in the thing actually working. Quietly.
          At scale. While you sleep.
        </p>
        <p>
          At <a href="https://cactusglobal.com" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Cactus Communications</a> I
          owned backend search infrastructure and designed multi-agent systems from scratch — the kind where you're
          debugging hallucinations at 2am and reverse-engineering why a cost spike appeared in last night's run. I
          reduced processing time by 80% and operational cost by 65%. Not because of one big insight. Because of a
          hundred small ones about <strong>where the waste actually lives in an agent pipeline.</strong>
        </p>
        <p>
          At <a href="https://gosunnyai.com" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">GoSunny AI</a> I was the technical
          co-builder as a consultant — scraping infrastructure, agentic qualification workflows, backend systems, and
          an LLM-driven nurture email pipeline for a US solar platform operating across 8 states. Essentially the
          engineering team, minus the headcount.
        </p>
        <p>
          My honest belief: most agentic systems today are over-engineered in the wrong places and under-controlled in
          the right ones. <strong
            >Models are evolving fast. If you wire them up carefully — right guardrails, right orchestration — cost and
            latency drop dramatically.</strong
          >
          Most teams haven't done this yet. That's the interesting problem.
        </p>
        <p>When I'm not building: chess, music, figuring out how businesses actually work. All systems with rules you spend years learning to bend.</p>
        <p>
          I just went independent. Building my own projects, writing publicly about what I learn, and open to working on
          ambitious things with people who care about doing it right. If a task is a no-brainer, it should be automated
          or skipped. If you want someone to think — <a href="#contact">let's talk.</a>
        </p>
      </div>
      <div class="hero-actions reveal d1">
        <a href="#projects" class="btn btn-fill">See my work</a>
        <a href="#writing" class="btn">Read my writing</a>
        <a href={calendlyUrl} class="btn" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Get in touch</a>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="stats-bar reveal d2">
      <div class="stat">
        <div class="stat-n">200<sup>M+</sup></div>
        <div class="stat-l">Searchable records</div>
      </div>
      <div class="stat">
        <div class="stat-n">1<sup>M+</sup></div>
        <div class="stat-l">Daily API requests</div>
      </div>
      <div class="stat">
        <div class="stat-n">80<sup>%</sup></div>
        <div class="stat-l">Processing time cut</div>
      </div>
      <div class="stat">
        <div class="stat-n">65<sup>%</sup></div>
        <div class="stat-l">Cost reduction</div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="section reveal" id="work">
      <div class="section-label">Experience</div>
      <h2>Where I've <em>worked</em></h2>

      <div class="exp-row">
        <div>
          <div class="exp-period">Mar 2023 – 2025</div>
          <div class="exp-co">Cactus Communications</div>
        </div>
        <div>
          <div class="exp-title">Software Engineer</div>
          <div class="exp-desc">
            Owned backend systems for large-scale search and AI workflows — <strong
              >200M+ searchable records, 1M+ daily API requests.</strong
            >
            Redesigned Elasticsearch infrastructure: index schema, sharding strategy, query optimization. Built production
            multi-agent systems using AutoGen with context-aware reasoning and state management. Then spent a lot of time
            making sure those agents didn't hallucinate, spike costs, or fall over. <strong
              >Reduced processing time 80%, operational cost 65%.</strong
            >
            Shipped on AWS (ECS, EC2, Lambda, SQS). Monitored everything with Grafana and Kibana, because production
            systems whisper before they scream.
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="exp-row">
        <div>
          <div class="exp-period">2024 – 2025</div>
          <div class="exp-co">GoSunny AI</div>
        </div>
        <div>
          <div class="exp-title">Tech Lead (Consultant)</div>
          <div class="exp-desc">
            GoSunny AI lets US homeowners get a solar quote, design, and financing agreement online — no
            commission-based salesperson required. I built the technical backbone: <strong
              >scraping infrastructure for lead sourcing, agentic qualification workflows, backend API layer, and an
              LLM-driven nurture email pipeline</strong
            > that moved cold leads toward signed installation agreements. The entire engineering function, compressed.
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="exp-row">
        <div>
          <div class="exp-period">Sep 2022 – Feb 2023</div>
          <div class="exp-co">Cactus Communications</div>
        </div>
        <div>
          <div class="exp-title">Software Engineer Intern</div>
          <div class="exp-desc">
            Real-time notification system on AWS Lambda + Slack. SQS-triggered async pipelines. S3 automation. The
            kind of infrastructure that's invisible when it's working and extremely visible when it isn't.
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="exp-row">
        <div>
          <div class="exp-period">Mar – Jun 2022</div>
          <div class="exp-co">Dotvik Solutions</div>
        </div>
        <div>
          <div class="exp-title">Full Stack Developer Intern</div>
          <div class="exp-desc">
            Redesigned order APIs — 90% processing efficiency gain. Email templating with Velocity engine. First real
            taste of making an existing system significantly faster by understanding it properly first.
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="section reveal" id="projects">
      <div class="section-label">Projects</div>
      <h2>Things I've <em>built</em></h2>

      <div class="project-row">
        <div>
          <div class="project-index">01</div>
          <div class="project-name">Ask R Discovery</div>
          <div class="project-tagline">AI Research Assistant</div>
          <p class="project-body">
            AI-powered research assistant for academics. Ask a complex research question, get a citation-backed answer.
            Under the hood: a multi-agent workflow — one agent for intent detection, one for document retrieval over
            large-scale research data, one for LLM-based summarization. The kind of system that looks simple until you try
            to make it consistently accurate.
          </p>
          <div class="project-tags">
            <span class="tag">Multi-agent</span><span class="tag">RAG</span>
            <span class="tag">FastAPI</span><span class="tag">Elasticsearch</span><span class="tag">LLM eval</span>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="project-aside">
          <a href="#" class="project-link">View →</a>
          <div class="project-status live">Live</div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="project-row">
        <div>
          <div class="project-index">02</div>
          <div class="project-name">LinkedIn AI Agent</div>
          <div class="project-tagline">Personal content engine — building in public</div>
          <p class="project-body">
            Crawls LinkedIn profiles of people whose content I want to learn from. Builds a knowledge base of their
            tone, hooks, and structure patterns. Every morning: 3 post ideas on WhatsApp, each grounded in trending
            topics and my knowledge base. I pick one, it drafts the post, sends it back for approval, then publishes.
            Zero manual work. The interesting part: teaching the agent what "sounds like me" actually means.
          </p>
          <div class="project-tags">
            <span class="tag">Agents</span><span class="tag">pgvector</span>
            <span class="tag">WhatsApp API</span><span class="tag">Apify</span><span class="tag">Buffer API</span>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="project-aside">
          <a href="#" class="project-link">Follow →</a>
          <div class="project-status wip">Building</div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="project-row">
        <div>
          <div class="project-index">03</div>
          <div class="project-name">Solar Lead Pipeline</div>
          <div class="project-tagline">GoSunny AI — Full-stack AI sales system</div>
          <p class="project-body">
            End-to-end AI pipeline for a US solar company across 8 states. Scraping for homeowner lead sourcing,
            agentic workflows for qualification, and an LLM-driven nurture email system. The goal: take a homeowner from
            "interested in solar" to a signed installation agreement — with no commission-based salesperson in the loop.
          </p>
          <div class="project-tags">
            <span class="tag">Scraping</span><span class="tag">Agentic workflows</span>
            <span class="tag">Email automation</span><span class="tag">FastAPI</span><span class="tag">AWS</span>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="project-aside">
          <a href="#" class="project-link">Case study →</a>
          <div class="project-status live">Shipped</div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="section reveal" id="writing">
      <div class="section-label">Writing</div>
      <h2>How I <em>think</em></h2>
      <div>
        {
          posts.map((post) => (
            <a class="writing-row" href={`${base}blog/${post.id}/`}>
              <span class="writing-date">{post.data.date}</span>
              <span class="writing-title">{post.data.title}</span>
              <span class="writing-cat">{(post.data.tags && post.data.tags[0]) || 'Writing'}</span>
            </a>
          ))
        }
        {
          writingTeasers.map((t) => (
            <a class="writing-row" href="#writing">
              <span class="writing-date">Coming soon</span>
              <span class="writing-title">{t.title}</span>
              <span class="writing-cat">{t.cat}</span>
            </a>
          ))
        }
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="contact-section reveal" id="contact">
      <div class="section-label" style="max-width:100%">Contact</div>
      <p class="contact-intro">
        If you're building something <em>ambitious</em> in the AI space and need someone who's actually shipped it in
        production — let's talk.
      </p>
      <p class="contact-body">
        I'm open to consulting on AI systems architecture, agentic workflow design, search infrastructure, or taking on
        ambitious full-stack builds end-to-end. Also just happy to talk to people who care about doing things right.
        No-brainer tasks need not apply.
      </p>
      <div class="contact-links">
        <a class="contact-link" href="mailto:aashuu.26m@gmail.com">
          aashuu.26m@gmail.com <span>Email →</span>
        </a>
        <a class="contact-link" href="https://linkedin.com/in/abhishekshukla" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">
          LinkedIn <span>Connect →</span>
        </a>
        <a class="contact-link" href={repoUrl} target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">
          GitHub <span>Code →</span>
        </a>
        <a class="contact-link" href={resumeUrl} target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">
          Resume <span>PDF →</span>
        </a>
        <a class="contact-link" href={calendlyUrl} target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">
          Book a call <span>Calendly →</span>
        </a>
      </div>
    </div>

    <footer>
      <span class="footer-t">© {year} Abhishek Shukla</span>
      <span class="footer-t">Rewa, India</span>
      <span class="footer-t"
        ><a href={repoUrl} target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Source</a> ·
        <a href={resumeUrl} target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Resume</a> ·
        <a href={calendlyUrl} target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Calendly</a></span
      >
    </footer>

    <script is:inline>
      const io = new IntersectionObserver(
        (entries) => {
          entries.forEach((e) => {
            if (e.isIntersecting) e.target.classList.add('up');
          });
        },
        { threshold: 0.07 },
      );
      document.querySelectorAll('.reveal').forEach((el) => io.observe(el));
      setTimeout(() => {
        document.querySelectorAll('.hero .reveal, .stats-bar').forEach((el) => el.classList.add('up'));
      }, 120);
    </script>
  </body>
</html>
